&nbsp;
And then the memory needs first of all unobtainable historical data. "The military judiciary and historians, after a difficult research work, lasted decades, have, so far, documented on the Italian territory five thousand cruel and infamous episodes of eccidi, reprisals, summary executions". A Nazi-fascist strategy to "make land burned around the partisans", "it was a serious crime of war, contrary to any international rule and military honor and, more so, to the principles of humanity". And again: "The infamy of the Marzabotto massacre, the greatest accomplishment in Italy, followed an equally unworthy corollary: the fascist propaganda, in the newspapers subjected to controls and censures, denied the undeniable, trying to deny the incident". But "totally submissive to Hitler's imperialist Germany, fascist Italy, entered the conflict without any respect for soldiers sent to die cynically, would not have had any escape." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
During the war the Italians changed judgment on fascism: "In the disastrous retreat of Russia, on the camps of El Alamein, in the brutal repressions carried out in Greece, in the Balkans, in Ethiopia, in the deportations of the Jews to the fields of extermination, in the support of the Nazis in the repression of the civilian population, the break between the Italian people and fascism," which "had long discovered his face, revealing his true brutal and inhuman traits".
&nbsp;
On September 8, the country was in absolute chaos. "But many Italians did not bow to dishonour. They chose the ransom route. A moral ransom, even before politicians," the President is still rebuilding. "The Resistance was born, a movement that, in its plurality of persons, motivations, proceeds and ideal thrusts, found its unity in the need to end Nazi rule on Italian territory, to establish a new cohabitation, founded on law and peace." A people made up of war veterans and young fans, peasants and intellectuals, monarchists and Republicans, joined "to fight, with weapons, against oppression and invader".
&nbsp;
